result.execSummary:
The defendant Daniel J Woydal was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (6th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

COURT SENTENCED Defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 42 MONTHS, with credit for 59 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 24 MONTHS. The Defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
The Defendant IS eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program ONLY after serving at least on-half (50%) of his Initial Confinement.
